ocs.github.com/en/copilot/reference/cli-command-reference\\\"},{\\\"title\\\":\\\"Using GitHub Copilot CLI - GitHub Docs\\\",\\\"url\\\":\\\"https://docs.github.com/en/copilot/how-tos/copilot-cli/use-copilot-cli\\\"},{\\\"title\\\":\\\"awesome-copilot/docs/README.hooks.md at main · github/awesome-copilot\\\",\\\"url\\\":\\\"https://github.com/github/awesome-copilot/blob/main/docs/README.hooks.md\\\"}]\\n\\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about GitHub Copilot CLI hooks configuration:\\n\\n## Configuration File Location\\n\\nCopilot agents load hook configuration files from .github/hooks/*.json in the repository. For GitHub Copilot CLI, hooks are loaded from your current working directory.\\n\\n## Configuration File Format\\n\\nYou configure hooks using a special JSON format. The JSON must contain a version field with a value of 1 and a hooks object containing arrays of hook definitions.\\n\\nHook configuration files use JSON format with version 1: { \\\"version\\\": 1, \\\"hooks\\\": { \\\"preToolUse\\\": [ { \\\"type\\\": \\\"command\\\", \\\"bash\\\": \\\"your-bash-command\\\", \\\"powershell\\\": \\\"your-powershell-command\\\", \\\"cwd\\\": \\\"optional/working/directory\\\", \\\"env\\\": { \\\"VAR\\\": \\\"value\\\" }, \\\"timeoutSec\\\": 30 } ] } }\\n\\n## File Naming\\n\\nIn the tutorial example, a hook configuration file is created at .github/hooks/copilot-cli-policy.json. The documentation also mentions that each hook is a folder containing a README.md file and a hooks.json configuration, though the specific naming convention can vary.\\n\\n## Available Hook Events\\n\\nAvailable hook events include: sessionStart (executed when a new agent session begins or when resuming an existing session), sessionEnd (executed when the agent session completes or is terminated), userPromptSubmitted (executed when the user submits a prompt to the agent), and preToolUse (executed before the agent uses any tool).\\n\\n\\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources